pr_title: emergency hotfix for account creation, v2
pr_body:
Retro comment:
I believe this was after a we refactored account creation and the indentation / nesting of logic was wrong s.t. if a email was not valid, we would attempt to fetch the account anyways and throw a server error

pr_title: Adding real time validation to signup
pr_body:
Issue: #3256 

Closes #1433

Todo:

- [x]  change api to check email id and screen name instead of hardwiring it to a true/false
- [x]  shift js to its respective directory and ask @jdlrobson for correct placement for js
- [x] change the function to use blur

pr_title: Canonical Books Page (Merging works & Editions UI)
pr_body:
<!-- What issue does this PR close? -->
Closes #684 :tada: 
Closes #3556 :tada: 
<!-- What does this PR achieve? [feature|hotfix|fix|refactor] -->

### Change Log

1. Adds sticky tab bar to books page
2. Show more / less collapse button
3. Books page chooses "best" (previewable) edition by default, shows selected edition in editions table
4. Search result shows cover consistent w/ available edition, sends to (3)
5. Adds editions table to the books page
6. Adds filter/search to editions table + ability to change # of results in table w/o reloading
7. Adds checkbox to List dropdown to control whether to add work v. edition to list
8. Adds "preview also available in" for various applicable languages
9. Fun / useless bookcover hover animation
10. Consolidates calls to action within sidebar + moves sidebar to the left, below bookcover

### Technical
<!-- What should be noted about the implementation? -->

- Merges the UI for /works and /books.
- URLs are not touched
- Lists are loaded multiple times on page (to enable showing edition + work results & separating locations of lists management from carousel/showcase)

### Code Review Checklist

- [x] Is everything i18n?
- [x] no inline styles
- [x] js in plugins/openlibrary/js/ where possible (except for templates/lists/widget.html)

### Known issues
- [x] BLOCKER: search results page items w/ no ocaid produce broken pages, e.g. "three body problem" ->
- [x] Read More link shouldn't display (for short descriptions / subject lists)
- [x] Styling on the `subjects` and pagination css affecting other pages (e.g. authors page) 
 https://dev.openlibrary.org/works/OL17335914W/The_Three-Body_Problem?edition=
- [x] #3556 Search result pages showing IA covers -- half fixed (when possible, we use the `openlibrary_edition` olid returned by the archive.org ES availability API. If the API has no `olid`, we fallback to archive.org (for now)
- [x] BWB buy-line too large for container (non-blocker)

Punting:
- [ ] Odd editions line flex formatting https://github.com/internetarchive/openlibrary/pull/3553#issuecomment-654504914
- [ ] #3554 if missing authors, styling breaks on book page -- on issue tracker

### Testing
<!-- Steps for reviewer to reproduce/verify what this PR does/fixes. -->

- [x] For each search result, book cover same as selected ocaid in the work title / borrow btn
- [x] Clicking on a search result cover goes to the works page w/ correct ocaid selected
- [x] Check lists behave correctly, both for work + edition 
- [x] LoanStatus: Borrowing, previews, and waitlists should work on books page
- [x] Changing editions should (currently) go to a /books URL

pr_title: Enabling public reading log at account creation
pr_body:
<!-- What issue does this PR close? -->
Closes #2058

[feature]

### Technical
<!-- What should be noted about the implementation? -->

1. There are two types of records for users, one is for their /people/xxx public `user`, the other is for their private `account` (e.g. encrypted password, email). Preferences and public settings, such as public_readinglog are stored on the `user` record.

2. An OpenLibraryAccount `account` record is not created for a user (nor their `user` record) until they have created + activated an InternetArchiveAccount and successfully logged in for their first time. At this point, the code we're adding will fetch the patron's **user** account and update their settings so their reading log is public by default.

### Testing
<!-- Steps for reviewer to reproduce/verify what this PR does/fixes. -->
Tested on dev (@mekarpeles + @tabshaikh)

### Screenshot
<!-- If this PR touches UI, please post evidence (screenshots) of it behaving correctly. -->

### Stakeholders
<!-- @ tag stakeholders of this bug -->

Let's double check this because I get the feeling this code is correct, just maybe in the wrong place. :) ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 14, 19, 6, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mekarpeles', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 425369490, 'comment_body': 'Okay, I too had the same question maybe we can pair program this to get through the finish line', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 14, 19, 9, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tabshaikh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 425382483, 'comment_body': '@mekarpeles Do we know somewhere that the user is logging in into his account for the first time, After verification?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 14, 19, 34, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tabshaikh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426050754, 'comment_body': 'Confirmed this code won't work as is:

If bookshelf_id = 0 then return books from all bookshelves. ```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 7, 22, 51, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cclauss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467319854, 'comment_body': "```suggestion for book in books: result[book['work_id']] = [ 'OL{}W'.format(book['work_id']), 'OL{}M'.format(book['edition_id']), mapping[book['bookshelf_id']], ] ```", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 7, 22, 58, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cclauss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467575318, 'comment_body': 'Inline styles to be fixed', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 12, 2, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tabshaikh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467575333, 'comment_body': 'Adding a line ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 12, 2, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tabshaikh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467594770, 'comment_body': '```suggestion ```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 15, 6, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tabshaikh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467607085, 'comment_body': "1. Let's make `bookshelf_id` a keyword arg which defaults to `None` and then we don't need to pass `0` in to the function call (the default will be all bookshelves). This makes more sense than having a reserved integer. 2. Also, when we do our check below, we'll want to specifically check `is None`. 3. and update this docstring comment :)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 17, 12, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mekarpeles', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467607325, 'comment_body': '`if bookshelf_id is None`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 17, 15, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mekarpeles', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467608066, 'comment_body': '`bookshelf_id` is declared to be an int so I would be more favorable to defaulting to 0 instead of None.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 17, 24, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cclauss', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467615365, 'comment_body': 'I think having a clear value separation between a case where all bookshelves should be considered v. a specific shelf considered is better served by a non-int value `None`, as otherwise the programmer is left to spend cognitive cycles wondering if an `id` or 0 is, could, or may eventually be a valid bookshelf ID. "If no bookshelf ID is provided, include all records" makes more intuitive sense than, "if the bookshelf_id happens to be the special value 0, which happens to be an integer, then don't actually limit by bookshelf_id 0, but instead include all bookshelves"', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 18, 43, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mekarpeles', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467615778, 'comment_body': 'It would be nice if this `limit` defaulted to `None`. Not a blocker; 10k seems like an arbitrary number', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 18, 47, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mekarpeles', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 467615913, 'comment_body': 'it may be nice to have the date in the filename, not a blocker, just adding for future context.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 9, 18, 49, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mekarpeles', 'type': 'User'}]
